TWO men have been bust for allegedly hijacking a truck transporting chicken and fish. The suspects, aged 19 and 36, were arrested in Philippi, Cape Town, on Wednesday, 27 July, while offloading a truck that was hijacked in Delft. Metro police spokeswoman Ruth Solomons said they were also found in possession of a signal jammer. “Just after 3pm, officers received information of a hijacked truck parked in Sport Road,” she said. ALSO READ | Cops on hunt for ATMs bombers! “Upon arrival, they spotted it with two suspects offloading cargo.” Solomons said the truck was carrying more than 600 boxes of chicken and fish, valued at about R200 000.  A woman who lives on the street where the men were bust said: “I saw the truck but I didn’t think it was stolen. ALSO READ | PICS: BLACK GLOVE izinkabi strike men in a Benz “They were offloading boxes and I thought the goods were meant for spaza shops. I was shocked when I heard that the vehicle was hijacked.” Captain Frederick van Wyk said: “The suspects were arrested after a tip-off from the public that meat was being offloaded from a truck. They are in detention and will appear in court soon.”